  "prompt": "How do calculate the gear ratio?",
  "response": "To calculate the gear ratio, you compare the number of teeth or the rotational speeds of two meshing gears. The gear ratio depends on whether you are calculating it based on the number of teeth or the rotational speeds of the gears.\n\n### **1. Gear Ratio Based on Teeth**\nIf you know the number of teeth on both gears, the gear ratio is calculated as:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Gear Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Number of Teeth on Driven Gear}}{\\text{Number of Teeth on Driving Gear}}\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n- **Driving Gear**: The gear that provides the input power.\n- **Driven Gear**: The gear that receives the power from the driving gear.\n\nFor example, if the driving gear has 20 teeth and the driven gear has 40 teeth, the gear ratio is:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Gear Ratio} = \\frac{40}{20} = 2\n\\]\n\nThis means the driven gear rotates once for every two rotations of the driving gear.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Gear Ratio Based on Rotational Speed**\nIf you know the rotational speeds (RPM) of the two gears, the gear ratio is calculated as:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Gear Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Speed of Driving Gear (RPM)}}{\\text{Speed of Driven Gear (RPM)}}\n\\]\n\nFor example, if the driving gear rotates at 100 RPM and the driven gear rotates at 50 RPM, the gear ratio is:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Gear Ratio} = \\frac{100}{50} = 2\n\\]\n\nThis means the driven gear rotates once for every two rotations of the driving gear.\n\n---\n\n### Notes:\n- A gear ratio greater than 1 indicates the driven gear rotates slower than the driving gear (speed reduction).\n- A gear ratio less than 1 indicates the driven gear rotates faster than the driving gear (speed increase).\n\nIf you're dealing with a gear train (multiple meshing gears), the overall gear ratio is the product of the individual gear ratios in the system.",
